It is no ordinary event to be able to offer the legendary years among the great clarets that read like history—1899, 1916, 1928, 1929, 1934 and 1937. Here are the great survivors of the noble years that have evoked unstinted praise in wine literature and at the dinner tables of the proprietors of the great chateaux of Bordeaux. Even the President of France, try- ing to please his most honored guests, could not offer greater aged wine classics than those clarets that appear below.

RARE PRE-WAR CLARETS

RARE PRE-WAR CLARETS

These wines are no longer commercially available. Most of them come from private cellars in France. To obtain wines of this age and calibre is akin to seeking out a Cezanne or Matisse. Here are wines to intrigue the col- lector. All are from impeccable sources, and will provide excellence when the cork is drawn.
